ss=\"wp-image-110\" srcset=\"https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/GU-website-photos-25-1024x819.png 1024w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/GU-website-photos-25-300x240.png 300w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/GU-website-photos-25-768x614.png 768w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/GU-website-photos-25.png 1500w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Garage door springs are what make your garage door feel &#8220;light.&#8221; Without them, your opener would never lift that heavy slab of metal. There are two main types of springs:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Torsion springs<\/strong>: Mounted above the garage door, they twist to create tension.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Extension springs<\/strong>: Located on either side of the door, they stretch and contract to lift it.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Each spring is designed to handle a specific number of cycles (one open and one close = one cycle), usually around 10,000 cycles. In a busy household, that might only last 7\u201310 years. Add in Austin\u2019s extreme heat, humidity, and occasional ice storms, and those springs take a beating.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>When a spring breaks, it can create a dangerous situation. The door may slam shut unexpectedly, stop halfway, or become crooked. That\u2019s not just inconvenient\u2014it\u2019s a major safety risk for your family.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Warning Signs You Need a Garage Door Spring Replacement<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>Wondering if your springs are on their last legs? Here are some red flags to look out for:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>The door only opens a few inches<\/strong> before stopping<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Loud snapping noise<\/strong> (like a firecracker) from the garage<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>The door feels extra heavy<\/strong> when trying to lift manually<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Uneven door movement<\/strong> or visible sagging<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>A visible gap in the spring<\/strong> or a stretched-out look<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>These symptoms are more than just annoying\u2014they signal that your garage system isn\u2019t working safely. And ignoring them could lead to more damage, or worse, an injury and why it may be time for a spring replacement.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Torsion Springs vs. Extension Springs: Which One Do You Have?<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"576\" src=\"https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"a technician using tools to repair a spring for an emergency garage door repair project. Spring replacement.\" class=\"wp-image-267\" srcset=\"https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-1024x576.jpg 1024w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-300x169.jpg 300w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-768x432.jpg 768w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/05\/Chris-Harrison-69-2048x1152.jpg 2048w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Knowing what type of spring your garage uses is key to understanding the repair process:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>Torsion springs<\/strong> are mounted horizontally above the garage door and offer smoother, more balanced lifting. They tend to last longer and are generally safer.<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>Extension springs<\/strong> run vertically along the tracks on either side of the door. They\u2019re more common in older homes and can be more dangerous if they fail.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Most modern Austin homes, especially newer builds in places like Cedar Park and Pflugerville, use torsion springs for their reliability. But no matter which type you have, Garage Up Austin can handle both with precision and care.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">The Dangers of DIY Spring Replacement (Don\u2019t Risk It!)<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<p>It might be tempting to fix a broken spring yourself. After all, how hard could it be? The truth is, it\u2019s very dangerous without the right tools and experience. Always call a professional for spring replacement.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Here\u2019s why you should avoid DIY spring repair:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li>Springs are under extreme tension and can snap back violently<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Incorrect removal can cause the door to slam shut or fall<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>You risk serious injury or damaging other parts of the system<\/li>\n\n\n\n<li>Warranties on parts and doors can be voided<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p>Professionals like our techs at Garage Up Austin use special winding bars, safety cables, and precise torque tools to handle the job safely. We\u2019ve seen what can go wrong, and trust us\u2014you don\u2019t want to learn the hard way.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Professional Garage Door Spring Replacement in Austin<\/h2>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"1024\" height=\"819\" src=\"https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/06\/GU-website-photos-9-1024x819.png\" alt=\"Garage Up full garage Renovation. \" class=\"wp-image-323\" srcset=\"https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/06\/GU-website-photos-9-1024x819.png 1024w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/06\/GU-website-photos-9-300x240.png 300w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/06\/GU-website-photos-9-768x614.png 768w, https:\/\/garageup.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2025\/06\/GU-website-photos-9.png 1500w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" \/><\/figure>\n\n\n\n<p>So, what does a 